WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.120
Look, Brian. Those are our motorcycles, David says.

00:08.340 --> 00:11.780
David and Brian are at Heathrow Airport

00:12.020 --> 00:16.760
in London. They are motorcycle racers from Enfield,

00:17.300 --> 00:28.160
a small town in England. They usually

00:28.160 --> 00:33.400
go to Brazil. Racers from many countries are

00:33.400 --> 00:37.140
going there too. They are all going to

00:37.140 --> 00:43.540
race across the Amazon jungle. Brian is reading

00:43.540 --> 00:44.260
a newspaper.

00:46.260 --> 00:51.340
Listen to this, David, he says. There's a

00:51.340 --> 00:55.800
problem in the Amazon. The Indians are very

00:55.800 --> 00:59.760
angry because miners are going into the jungle.

01:01.280 --> 01:05.880
The miners are taking their homes. But David

01:06.360 --> 01:10.320
isn't listening to Brian. The race is going

01:10.320 --> 01:16.240
to be good, he says. Yes, and difficult,

01:16.600 --> 01:16.900
David.

01:19.580 --> 01:23.200
Two days later, the racers are in Brasilia.

01:24.080 --> 01:28.320
Brian and David are there too. A lot

01:28.320 --> 01:29.620
of people come and

01:29.620 --> 01:34.880
watch. It is a beautiful sunny morning. There

01:34.880 --> 01:38.260
is a lot of noise. People are talking

01:38.260 --> 01:39.220
to the racers.

01:40.180 --> 01:45.660
Photographers are taking pictures. The race is going

01:45.660 --> 01:49.080
to start, a young man says. Listen.

01:50.140 --> 01:55.180
Good morning, a man says. This is the

01:55.180 --> 02:00.480
start of the Amazon rally. 42 people are

02:00.480 --> 02:01.460
going to race

02:01.460 --> 02:06.640
from here to Manaus. Are you okay, Brian?

02:07.540 --> 02:13.440
David asks. No, Brian answers. I've got a

02:13.440 --> 02:15.260
problem. Look,

02:16.140 --> 02:19.000
oil is leaking from the engine of my

02:19.000 --> 02:19.560
motorcycle.

02:21.580 --> 02:25.640
Where's that glue for oil leaks? Brian asks.

02:26.780 --> 02:29.120
The racers are putting on their helmets.

02:30.040 --> 02:35.500
Here, try this, David says. He gives Brian

02:35.500 --> 02:39.260
some glue. Brian puts some glue on his

02:39.260 --> 02:39.700
engine,

02:40.160 --> 02:44.460
but it comes out very slowly. Quickly, Brian,

02:45.160 --> 02:48.860
the race is going to start, David says.

02:50.140 --> 02:55.000
But oil is leaking from Brian's engine. Quickly,

02:55.600 --> 03:02.040
David says again. The oil stops. Brian puts

03:02.040 --> 03:02.340
on

03:02.340 --> 03:06.660
his helmet and gets on his motorcycle. The

03:06.660 --> 03:09.860
engines of the motorcycles make a lot of

03:09.860 --> 03:10.200
noise.

03:11.500 --> 03:16.380
The race is starting, David says. Let's go,

03:17.000 --> 03:20.940
Brian says. The Amazon rally starts.

03:22.160 --> 03:27.640
The first day is okay. The roads are

03:27.640 --> 03:32.260
good. The racers see many small towns and

03:32.260 --> 03:32.560
villages.

03:33.820 --> 03:36.800
People stand near the road and watch them.

03:38.220 --> 03:41.780
On the second day, the roads are not

03:41.780 --> 03:42.660
very good.

03:43.540 --> 03:48.360
Two Italians, Luigi and Enrico, are in first

03:48.360 --> 03:49.580
and second place.

03:50.860 --> 03:54.500
On the third day, the racers are in

03:54.500 --> 03:57.880
the jungle. The roads are very bad.

03:59.320 --> 04:02.300
The Brazilians are in first and second place

04:02.300 --> 04:08.220
now. Then, come Luigi and Enrico, David and

04:08.220 --> 04:10.880
Brian are behind the two Italians.

04:12.660 --> 04:16.280
The race always stops late in the afternoon.

04:17.580 --> 04:22.060
Those Brazilians are very good and they know

04:22.060 --> 04:24.720
the road, Brian says that evening.

04:26.680 --> 04:30.800
The Brazilians aren't a problem. The rain is

04:30.800 --> 04:34.580
our big problem. Look, David answers.

04:39.280 --> 04:44.220
Day four. This is our second day in

04:44.220 --> 04:49.380
the jungle. A difficult day. The rain never

04:49.380 --> 04:52.620
stops and the road is very bad.

04:53.620 --> 04:58.480
There are trees across the roads. Sometimes, we

04:58.480 --> 05:00.380
can't stay on our motorcycles.

05:01.980 --> 05:06.100
I am first in the race now and

05:06.100 --> 05:10.920
David is second. The two Italians are behind

05:10.920 --> 05:13.940
us. We are happy about that.

05:15.860 --> 05:19.140
It is seven o'clock now and it

05:19.140 --> 05:23.760
is very dark. The days are very hot

05:23.760 --> 05:27.880
in the jungle. But the nights are beautiful.

05:29.680 --> 05:34.040
David is in bed. I am going to

05:34.040 --> 05:34.800
bed, too.

05:38.080 --> 05:40.980
The race starts very early on the third

05:40.980 --> 05:45.580
day in the jungle. In the afternoon, Brian

05:45.580 --> 05:46.780
and David stop.

05:47.980 --> 05:52.080
The jungle is very beautiful, but they aren't

05:52.080 --> 05:55.500
looking at it. They are looking for the

05:55.500 --> 05:57.420
town of Una Una.

05:59.120 --> 06:04.520
Where are we now, Brian asks? I don't

06:04.520 --> 06:08.560
know. Is this the road to Una Una?

06:09.460 --> 06:12.560
I don't know, David says again.

06:13.960 --> 06:18.960
Where are the racers, Brian asks? Can you

06:18.960 --> 06:22.920
hear them? They stop their engines and listen.

06:23.720 --> 06:28.960
The jungle is quiet. Then they hear a

06:28.960 --> 06:29.220
noise.

06:30.300 --> 06:36.320
Listen, David, Brian says. What is it? David

06:36.320 --> 06:40.940
asks. It isn't a motorcycle, Brian answers.

06:42.400 --> 06:46.660
Suddenly they see some men. They are walking

06:46.660 --> 06:48.120
to Brian and David.

06:49.260 --> 06:54.240
Look at those men, David. Brian says. Who

06:54.240 --> 06:59.700
are they? David asks. They aren't racers, David.

07:00.660 --> 07:02.420
They are Indians.

07:04.600 --> 07:07.760
The Indians come and talk to Brian and

07:07.760 --> 07:11.320
David, but the two young men can't understand

07:11.320 --> 07:11.880
them.

07:13.180 --> 07:18.520
These Indians are very angry, Brian. But why?

07:19.440 --> 07:23.100
I don't know. I can't understand them.

07:24.260 --> 07:30.340
We've got a problem, Brian, David says. The

07:30.340 --> 07:33.080
Indians take the two young men to an

07:33.080 --> 07:33.860
Indian village.

07:34.640 --> 07:38.620
A woman with blue eyes comes and talks

07:38.620 --> 07:44.060
to Brian and David. Her name's Astrid and

07:44.060 --> 07:44.840
she's German.

07:46.620 --> 07:49.740
She lives in the jungle because she's working

07:49.740 --> 07:50.860
there with the Indians.

07:52.340 --> 07:57.540
Who are you? The woman asks. I'm Brian

07:57.540 --> 08:00.300
and this is my friend David.

08:01.380 --> 08:07.500
Why are the Indians angry? David asks. Are

08:07.500 --> 08:12.140
you miners? The miners want this place.

08:13.120 --> 08:16.400
Sometimes they come here and they kill the

08:16.400 --> 08:22.880
Indians, Astrid says. We aren't miners. We are

08:22.880 --> 08:23.360
motorcycle

08:23.360 --> 08:27.800
racers, David says. We want to go to

08:27.800 --> 08:33.720
Una Una. Astrid talks to Maoni, the Indian

08:33.720 --> 08:34.280
chief.

08:35.720 --> 08:40.500
Maoni listens and talks to his men. They

08:40.500 --> 08:41.700
aren't angry now.

08:44.120 --> 08:47.720
The miners are coming to the village, Astrid

08:47.720 --> 08:51.060
says. Chief Maoni knows that

08:52.020 --> 08:56.460
they're going to kill his men. Let's get

08:56.460 --> 08:58.820
the police Astrid, Brian says.

08:59.800 --> 09:05.080
How? There's no time. I can go to

09:05.080 --> 09:09.220
Una Una. There's a police station there, Brian

09:09.220 --> 09:09.600
says.

09:10.720 --> 09:13.660
But you don't know the road to Una

09:13.660 --> 09:18.980
Una, David says. Astrid and Chief Maoni talk

09:18.980 --> 09:19.420
again.

09:21.500 --> 09:24.960
Kawak is going to go to Una Una

09:24.960 --> 09:29.900
with you tomorrow. He's Chief Maoni's son and

09:29.900 --> 09:32.600
he knows the road, Astrid says.

09:36.940 --> 09:40.140
At seven o'clock in the morning, Brian

09:40.140 --> 09:43.200
and Kawak get on Brian's motorcycle.

09:44.480 --> 09:49.480
Kawak isn't very happy. He doesn't know about

09:49.480 --> 09:53.500
motorcycles. The Indians watch them.

09:54.700 --> 09:58.980
Brian starts the engine and Kawak gets off

09:58.980 --> 10:02.920
the motorcycle quickly. The Indians run to the

10:02.920 --> 10:03.220
trees.

10:05.220 --> 10:09.180
Astrid talks to Kawak. Then he gets on

10:09.180 --> 10:10.640
the motorcycle again.

10:11.300 --> 10:16.380
The Indians watch from the trees. Brian starts

10:16.380 --> 10:17.600
the engine again.

10:19.140 --> 10:24.520
Go, David says. Brian and Kawak take the

10:24.520 --> 10:26.320
road to Una Una.

10:28.220 --> 10:31.900
It is difficult in the jungle, but Brian

10:31.900 --> 10:35.580
is a good racer and Kawak knows the

10:35.580 --> 10:35.840
road.

10:36.480 --> 10:39.820
He knows every river and tree in the

10:39.820 --> 10:40.040
jungle.

10:42.080 --> 10:45.200
Early in the afternoon, they come to a

10:45.200 --> 10:49.080
big river. Brian looks in his roadbook.

10:50.100 --> 10:54.620
They are near Una Una now. Then Brian

10:54.620 --> 10:55.800
looks at the engine.

10:56.760 --> 11:01.420
Oh no! Oil is leaking from the engine

11:01.420 --> 11:05.720
again, he thinks. He stops the motorcycle.

11:07.360 --> 11:11.720
I haven't got any glue. Where's David's glue?

11:12.520 --> 11:12.820
He thinks.

11:14.000 --> 11:16.920
This time I've got a big problem.

11:18.880 --> 11:23.280
Kawak looks at the oil. Then he walks

11:23.280 --> 11:26.100
to a tree and takes a green fruit.

11:27.280 --> 11:29.840
He puts the fruit on the hot engine.

11:31.140 --> 11:32.740
The leak stops.

11:34.160 --> 11:39.440
That's very good, Brian says. Thank you, Kawak.

11:40.220 --> 11:41.200
Let's go!

11:42.500 --> 11:47.380
They start to drive again. The oil often

11:47.380 --> 11:48.500
leaks from the engine,

11:49.340 --> 11:51.940
but Kawak stops it with the green fruit

11:51.940 --> 11:56.520
every time. They arrive in Una Una in

11:56.520 --> 11:57.020
the evening.

11:58.460 --> 12:02.020
They meet Captain Silver at the police station,

12:02.700 --> 12:04.440
and Brian talks to him.

12:05.720 --> 12:09.900
The miners are coming, Captain. They're going to

12:09.900 --> 12:12.280
kill the Indians, Brian says.

12:13.660 --> 12:17.600
You're right, young man. We don't have much

12:17.600 --> 12:18.100
time.

12:19.120 --> 12:23.160
Captain Silver talks to a policeman. Let's go

12:23.160 --> 12:26.700
to the Indian village. I want 20 men.

12:27.620 --> 12:27.980
Quickly.

12:29.920 --> 12:32.960
They get to the Indian village late in

12:32.960 --> 12:33.620
the afternoon.

12:34.840 --> 12:38.740
Let's wait for the miners, Captain Silver says.

12:39.640 --> 12:41.080
Go behind the trees.

12:42.820 --> 12:46.840
It's night again. They are all waiting for

12:46.840 --> 12:47.240
the miners.

12:49.140 --> 12:53.140
Look, Captain Silver says. They're coming.

12:54.860 --> 12:58.520
The miners are coming from the jungle. They're

12:58.520 --> 12:59.980
moving very quietly.

13:01.040 --> 13:03.460
There are a lot of miners in the

13:03.460 --> 13:06.740
village now. They are looking for the Indians.

13:08.360 --> 13:13.720
The village is quiet. Then Captain Silver says,

13:14.720 --> 13:20.280
this is Captain Silver. Don't move! The miners

13:20.280 --> 13:22.960
run, and the Indians run too.

13:23.640 --> 13:27.500
They make a lot of noise. Two miners

13:27.500 --> 13:30.000
find David and catch him.

13:31.180 --> 13:35.820
They're going to kill me, David thinks. But

13:35.820 --> 13:40.400
then two policemen run to him. Stop, they

13:40.400 --> 13:40.680
say.

13:41.520 --> 13:42.300
We are policemen.

13:42.300 --> 13:49.200
In the morning, Chief Maune and his people

13:49.200 --> 13:53.740
are very happy. A lot of Indians are

13:53.740 --> 13:54.020
dancing.

13:55.840 --> 14:00.140
Chief Maune has two beautiful necklaces in his

14:00.140 --> 14:04.360
hands. He smiles and gives a red necklace

14:04.360 --> 14:05.080
to David.

14:06.640 --> 14:11.800
Jaguarri, he says. He's giving you an Indian

14:11.800 --> 14:17.610
name, Astrid says. Jaguarri is a small jaguar.

14:19.180 --> 14:23.520
Then Chief Maune gives a black necklace to

14:23.520 --> 14:23.800
Brian.

14:25.200 --> 14:31.560
Manui, he says. Quick runner, Astrid says.

14:32.980 --> 14:39.740
Brian gives his helmet to Kowak. Champion, he

14:39.740 --> 14:42.320
says. They all smile.

14:44.800 --> 14:49.080
Captain Silver takes Brian and David to Manaus.

14:49.980 --> 14:54.000
The races are there. There are photographers too.

14:54.880 --> 14:58.900
They are taking pictures of the champions, Luigi

14:58.900 --> 15:05.720
and Enrico, the two Italians. Brian, David, hello.

15:06.880 --> 15:11.980
Enrico says, Look, we are the champions, Luigi

15:11.980 --> 15:16.520
says. Congratulations, Brian and David say.

15:17.320 --> 15:22.460
Are you okay? Enrico asks. Now we are,

15:23.140 --> 15:28.360
Brian says. Brian and David's talk to Enrico

15:28.360 --> 15:31.620
and Luigi about the Indians and the miners.

15:32.860 --> 15:39.320
Your champions too, Luigi says. Yes, they're champions

15:39.320 --> 15:43.820
of a very important race, Captain Silver says.

15:45.620 --> 15:49.140
Brian and David look at their Indian necklaces.

15:50.200 --> 15:54.760
Congratulations, Manui, David says to his friend.

15:56.380 --> 16:00.140
Congratulations, Jaguarri, Brian says.

